# Deep Strike Campaign Mode Walkthrough

The Peacock Engine has successfully split its operational logic. You basically now have two massive execution paths for high-stakes AI automation.

## 1. The Monolithic Pipeline (Mode A)
This is exactly the system you started with: 10 fixed sequences firing a single compiled block of instructions and payloads. It remains completely insulated and untouched when you select the `MONOLITHIC MODE` button at the top of the engineering pane.

## 2. The Campaign Operation (Mode B)
By selecting `CAMPAIGN MODE` at the top of the Payload Striker grid, you flip the architecture from flat lists into a deeply hierarchical operation sequence.

### A. Strike Groups (Loadout Builder)
The active payload bay converts into the "Loadout Builder". 
- You generate isolated blocks called **Strike Groups**.
- Each Strike Group accepts one **Primary Directive (Instruction)**.
- You can load 1, 10, or 100 raw payloads (Ammo) underneath that Strike Group by dragging/clicking from the main Vault Pile.


### B. Dynamic Sequencing 

When you build these groups, the Campaign engine calculates exactly how many payloads you've attached across all of your groups. 
The right-hand **Tactical Manifest** sidebar sheds the static 10-slot visual and replaces it with a dynamic, infinite grid showing the precise amount of strikes sitting in the queue. 

**Example Workflow**:
1. You spin up Group `Alpha`. You give it Instruction: *"Find all exposed API keys"*. You drop 25 files into it.
2. You spin up Group `Beta`. You give it Instruction: *"Translate inline comments to Spanish"*. You drop 5 files into it.
3. You check your Tactical Manifest on the right. It will exactly show a 30-slot pending queue.
4. You hit launch. 

The Orchestrator loops through Group `Alpha`, sending each of the 25 files up isolated with its associated instruction. Then it seamlessly moves into Group `Beta` and fires the remaining 5 files using the secondary translation instruction. 

Everything runs consecutively, scaling precisely to the size of the operation. Code built cleanly. Ready to deploy via `.git`.

